Data Cleaning and processing

# Drop token (useless col)
Token <- RecordDF_A$token
RecordDF_A<-RecordDF_A[-c(1)]

# Train test split
DataSize=nrow(RecordDF_A) ## how many rows?
TrainingSet_Size<-floor(DataSize*(3/4)) ## Size for training set
TestSet_Size <- DataSize - TrainingSet_Size ## Size for testing set

set.seed(123)
MyTrainSample <- sample(nrow(RecordDF_A),
                                    TrainingSet_Size,replace=FALSE)

# training data
MyTrainingSET <- RecordDF_A[MyTrainSample,]
# table(MyTrainingSET$Quotes_label)

# testing data
MyTestSET <- RecordDF_A[-MyTrainSample,]
# table(MyTestSET$Quotes_label)

# true label of test data
TestKnownLabels <- MyTestSET$Quotes_label
MyTestSET <- MyTestSET[ , -which(names(MyTestSET) %in% c("Quotes_label"))]

Decision Tree 1

Visualization

DT <- rpart::rpart(MyTrainingSET$Quotes_label ~ ., data = MyTrainingSET, method="class")
rattle::fancyRpartPlot(DT,main = "Decision Tree 1")

Confusion matrix

DT_Prediction= predict(DT, MyTestSET, type="class")
table(DT_Prediction,TestKnownLabels) 
##                TestKnownLabels
## DT_Prediction   High position Low position Middle
##   High position            11            2      0
##   Low position              1           10      9
##   Middle                    2            2      7

Discussion and analysis

In this decision tree, the parameters are set as default (GINI).

Of all nodes, the root node is DEMA, then is ARRONUP, and the third is HT_TRENDLINE. In the confusion matrix, the accuracy of the prediction performs well in predicting the “High position” and “Middle Position”, while a worse prediction on “Low position”. Almost half of the “Low position” is wrong classified into the “Middle”.

Decision Tree 2

Visualization

DT2<-rpart(MyTrainingSET$Quotes_label ~ ., data = MyTrainingSET,cp=0.05, method="class")
rattle::fancyRpartPlot(DT2,main = "Decision Tree 2")

Confusion matrix

DT_Prediction2= predict(DT2, MyTestSET, type = "class")
table(DT_Prediction2,TestKnownLabels)
##                TestKnownLabels
## DT_Prediction2  High position Low position Middle
##   High position            11            2      0
##   Low position              2           11      9
##   Middle                    1            1      7

Discussion and analysis

In this decision tree, the Cross-entropy is set as the criteria of splitting nodes, while others are kept.

“DEMA” takes a vital role when recognizing the “High position” trend.

Although the “cp” is set with a little value of 0.05, “DEMA” and “AROONUP” are still the most important financial indicator when analyzing the trend of the time series.

Compared with the previous tree, the accuracy of predicting the “Middle” improved a bit with the cost of predicting the “Low position”.

Decision Tree 3

Visualization

## Let's make a third tree - here we use cp = 0 and 
## "information" instead of the default which is GINI
DT3<-rpart(MyTrainingSET$Quotes_label ~ ., 
           data = MyTrainingSET,cp=0.1, method="class",
           parms = list(split="information"),minsplit=1)
rattle::fancyRpartPlot(DT3,main="Decision Tree")

Confusion matrix

# DT3$variable.importance
DT_Prediction3= predict(DT3, MyTestSET, type = "class")
table(DT_Prediction3,TestKnownLabels)
##                TestKnownLabels
## DT_Prediction3  High position Low position Middle
##   High position            11            2      0
##   Low position              2           11      9
##   Middle                    1            1      7

Discussion and analysis

In this decision tree, the splitting criteria are set with the “information gain” with a small “cp” value.

The root feature is still the “DEMA”.

The biggest difference compared with previous plots is that “AROONDOWN” ranks the second financial technical indicator rather than the AROONUP. Along with this change, the prediction accuracy on “Low position” has been increased a bit.Summary

Conclusion 1

DEMA and ARRON are both useful key technical indicators when recognizing the time series trend, especially in the high position and steady position. Among 26 technical indicators, the key question is to figure out which technical indicator is useful when recognizing the quotes trend, which may be very important in quantitative analysis on the finance quotes. With this project, “DEMA” and “ARRON” perform well in doing such a job. One of the practical works of this result is that it ould be used as a quantitative trading signal, such as the “Following trading strategy”, where buying in in the high position and selling in the low position.

Conclusion 2

Predicting market reaction to the high position will be simpler than that to the low position. During the project, no matter the splitting criteria is, cross-entropy loss, GINI, and even information gain, the prediction accuracy on recognizing the low position is lower than the high position. Since this technical signal implies the core reaction of the market emotion, the harder prediction, the more chaos the market is. The result of the project also conforms to the intuition, where it is harder to predict the bottom of the market than predict the top of the market, where it is harder to sell shares in loss than shares in profit Psychologically.
